        <!-- 2. ACTIVITY 1 (WAVE) -->
        <section id="activity1" class="activity-section">
            <h1>Activity 1: Wave Energy for Desalination</h1>
            <h3>Question: Draw the block diagram of a wave energy conversion system that can be integrated into a coastal desalination plant. (Activity 1 - Tidal/Wave/Wind)</h3>

            <h4>Block Diagram/Architecture (Oscillating Water Column $\rightarrow$ RO Desalination)</h4>
            <div class="block-diagram">
                <span>WAVE POWER INPUT</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>WEC CONVERTER (OWC Chamber)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>AIR TURBINE</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>GENERATOR</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>ELECTRICAL POWER OUTPUT</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>HIGH-PRESSURE PUMP (Desalination)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>RO MEMBRANE</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>FRESHWATER OUTPUT</span>
            </div>

            <h4>Explanation (195 Words)</h4>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p>This activity proposes integrating a **Wave Energy Conversion (WEC)** system with a **Reverse Osmosis (RO)** desalination plant. The **source of energy** is the kinetic and potential energy inherent in ocean waves. The most common **conversion process** for this integration is often an **Oscillating Water Column (OWC)** device, where incoming waves compress air within a chamber. This pressurized air drives a **Wells Turbine** (or similar), converting the wave's kinetic energy into **mechanical energy**, which a generator then transforms into **electrical power**.</p>
                <p>The **output/utilization** of this system is two-fold: **electricity** and **potable freshwater**. The generated electricity powers the high-pressure pumps essential for the RO desalination process, which forces seawater through semi-permeable membranes to remove salt. This system's **real-world application relevance** is significant for coastal regions facing water scarcity. By using a non-intermittent, non-polluting wave resource to power an energy-intensive desalination process, it provides a completely self-sufficient, sustainable solution for clean water access, reducing reliance on the main electrical grid and fossil fuels.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 3. ACTIVITY 2 (BIOMASS) -->
        <section id="activity2" class="activity-section">
            <h1>Activity 2: Biogas Generation for a Dairy Farm</h1>
            <h3>Question: Design a biomass-based biogas generation system for a dairy farm handling 100 cattle. (Activity 2 - Biomass)</h3>

            <h4>Block Diagram/Architecture (Anaerobic Digestion System)</h4>
            <div class="block-diagram">
                <span>CATTLE MANURE/SLURRY (Feedstock)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>PREPROCESSING/MIXING TANK</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>ANAEROBIC DIGESTER ($\text{CH}_4 + \text{CO}_2$ Generation)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>BIOGAS STORAGE</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>BIOGAS UTILIZATION (Heating/Electricity)</span>
                <br>
                <span>&nbsp;</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>DIGESTATE OUTPUT (Slurry)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>FERTILIZER UTILIZATION</span>
            </div>

            <h4>Explanation (190 Words)</h4>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p>The objective is to design a sustainable biogas generation system for a dairy farm. The primary **source of energy** is the **biomass** in the form of **cattle manure** and wastewater slurry from the 100 cattle. The **conversion process** is **Anaerobic Digestion (AD)**, which occurs in a large, airtight digester tank. Microorganisms break down the organic material in the absence of oxygen, resulting in the production of **biogas** (primarily methane ($\text{CH}_4$) and carbon dioxide ($\text{CO}_2$)) and a nutrient-rich residue called **digestate**.</p>
                <p>The main **output/utilization** of the system is the **biogas**, which is stored and typically used on the farm for thermal applications like cooking, heating water for cleaning, or fueling a generator for electricity. The secondary, but equally valuable, output is the **digestate**, a superior, odor-free **organic fertilizer** that can replace chemical fertilizers on the farmâ€™s fodder fields. The **real-world application relevance** for dairy farms is transformative. It simultaneously manages massive volumes of farm waste hygienically, reduces greenhouse gas emissions (by capturing methane), provides a renewable energy source, and creates a valuable fertilizer byproduct, significantly boosting the farm's environmental and economic sustainability.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 4. ACTIVITY 3 (OTEC) -->
        <section id="activity3" class="activity-section">
            <h1>Activity 3: Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion (OTEC)</h1>
            <h3>Question: Develop the block diagram of an Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion (OTEC) system for electricity production and freshwater generation. (Activity 3 - Geothermal/OTEC)</h3>

            <h4>Block Diagram/Architecture (Closed-Cycle OTEC System)</h4>
            <div class="block-diagram">
                <span>WARM SURFACE WATER ($\approx 25^\circ \text{C}$)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>EVAPORATOR (Vaporizes Working Fluid)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>TURBINE</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>GENERATOR (Electricity)</span>
                <br>
                <span>&nbsp;</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>CONDENSER (Cooled by Deep Water)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>COLD DEEP WATER ($\approx 5^\circ \text{C}$)</span> &nbsp; $\rightarrow$ &nbsp; 
                <span>DISCHARGE</span>
            </div>

            <h4>Explanation (199 Words)</h4>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p>This activity details a **Closed-Cycle Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion (OTEC)** system, which utilizes the temperature difference between warm surface seawater and cold deep seawater. The **source of energy** is the enormous stored thermal energy in the ocean, a result of solar heating. The most common and efficient **conversion process** is the **Closed-Cycle OTEC**, which uses a low-boiling-point working fluid, such as ammonia. Warm surface water heats this fluid in an **evaporator** to create high-pressure vapor. This vapor drives a **turbine** connected to a **generator** to produce electricity. The vapor is then cooled back into a liquid in a **condenser** using cold water pumped from the ocean depths, completing the closed cycle.</p>
                <p>The primary **output/utilization** is continuous, reliable **baseload electricity generation**. A secondary benefit, often integrated with **Open-Cycle OTEC**, is the production of **freshwater** from the condensed steam, which is a key value proposition. OTECâ€™s **real-world application relevance** lies in its potential to provide a non-intermittent, clean energy source for tropical island nations and coastal developing regions. As the temperature gradient is consistently available $24/7$, OTEC avoids the intermittency issues of solar and wind, offering a stable power supply and potentially alleviating clean water shortages simultaneously.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

    </div>
</div>

<script>
    /* JavaScript to handle smooth navigation and display the correct section */
    function showActivity(activityId, element) {
        // Hide all sections
        document.querySelectorAll('.activity-section').forEach(section => {
            section.classList.remove('active');
        });

        // Show the selected section
        const targetSection = document.getElementById(activityId);
        if (targetSection) {
            targetSection.classList.add('active');
        }

        // Update active class on sidebar links
        document.querySelectorAll('#sidebar ul li a').forEach(link => {
            link.classList.remove('active');
        });
        if (element) {
            element.classList.add('active');
        }
    }

    // Initial load: determine which section to show based on the URL hash or default to 'welcome'
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
        const hash = window.location.hash.substring(1);
        let activityToShow = 'welcome';
        
        if (hash && document.getElementById(hash)) {
            activityToShow = hash;
        }

        const navElement = document.getElementById('nav-' + activityToShow);
        showActivity(activityToShow, navElement);

        // Optional: Scroll to the top of the content area on navigation change (for mobile view)
        const contentDiv = document.getElementById('content');
        if (contentDiv) {
            contentDiv.scrollTop = 0;
        }
    });

    // Ensure the hash changes the displayed content when clicking links
    document.querySelectorAll('#sidebar a').forEach(link => {
        link.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
            e.preventDefault();
            const activityId = e.target.getAttribute('href').substring(1);
            window.location.hash = activityId; // Update URL hash
            showActivity(activityId, e.target);
            
            // Scroll to the top of the content area
            const contentDiv = document.getElementById('content');
            if (contentDiv) {
                contentDiv.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
            }
        });
    });
</script>

